The Hawks believe the blades were deliberately planted and could have caused serious damage to a player if he came in contact with the blade, Nine News reports.

Thousands of fans, many of which were children,  took to the field following the open session and potentially could have been injured by the razors too.

Hawthorn chief executive, Stuart Fox, told the Herald Sun  he was deeply concerned but had ensured no players were in danger when training resumed.

'We can confirm there were some razor blades found and we took immediate action and scoured the ground before the players went out,' he told the newspaper.

'We are fortunate that no one was hurt and disappointed that someone would go to that extreme and put our players in jeopardy.'  

